main event: Multiple sightings of unidentified flying objects were reported in Washington, D.C. in 1957, including visual observations of silver or chrome cigar-shaped objects maneuvering for 30 minutes, as well as white lights stationary for several seconds before moving rapidly at high speeds and disappearing behind clouds.
interesting points: The sightings included observations of two unidentified objects in Washington, D.C. in 1957.
One sighting described a white light, about the size of a penny, stationary before moving off rapidly in a straight line at an estimated speed of at least 1000 miles per hour.
The witness who observed the white light was the Chief of Maintenance Division at the U.S. Weather Bureau in Washington, D.C.
The behavior of one of the observed objects was noted to be more likely caused by a natural phenomenon than an aircraft.
The conclusion for one of the sightings indicated that it was likely a balloon, aircraft, or astronomical satellite due to insufficient data for evaluation.
witnesses: multiple witnesses including Chief of Maintenance Division at the U.S. Weather Bureau
